{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":4307,"record_hash":"sha256:b270744da5822004df1f9d8b357281fe8d567832b55b008f237245ab7e67542d","timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:21:32.917Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: d0626a\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 797\nOutput:\n\nUse `skim` first when the goal is to recover enough turn history to continue:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog skim\nbut agentlog skim branch main\n```\n\n`skim` is intentionally a porcelain command. It loads all related matches,\nsorts sessions chronologically, and returns a compact table-of-contents entry\nfor every turn in every related session. JSON keeps full session/turn handles\nfor follow-up reads. Do not call this \"full context\"; it is the related turn\nhistory in abbreviated form.\n\nUse the drill-down commands when `skim` is too thin, ambiguous, missing the\nwhy, or the exact transcript detail matters. Do not start by dumping full\nrecords; skim should be enough for orientation.\n\n1. Start from a target and skim all related sessions in chronological order.\n2. If the human skim is enough, stop.\n3. If detail is needed, rerun skim as JSON to get `session_key` / `turn_key`.\n4. Hydrate bounded records only for the turn that needs detail.\n\nExample:\n\n```sh\nbut --json agentlog skim branch main\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --limit 20\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --limit 50\n```\n\nThe goal is orientation first, payload later. Do not start by dumping full\nrecords for every related session; that loses the signal these commands are\ntrying to preserve.\n\n`sessions` is mostly a session inventory/debugging command now. Normal agent\nrecovery should be `skim`, then JSON `skim` plus `show` only when exact detail\nis needed.\n\n### Target Discovery\n\nWhen the user says \"current branch\" or gives no explicit target, inspect\nGitButler state first:\n\n```sh\nbut status\n```\n\nIf plain Git reports `gitbutler/workspace`, do not use that as the agentlog\nbranch target. Use `but status` to find the applied GitButler branch/stack name,\nthen query:\n\n```sh\nbut --json agentlog skim branch <gitbutler-branch-name>\n```\n\nRunning `but agentlog skim` without an explicit target performs this\nGitButler branch discovery automatically. Pass an explicit target when working\nfrom a review or change rather than the applied branch.\n\n### Reading `sessions`\n\nUse `sessions` to answer \"which captured sessions are probably relevant to this\ntarget?\"\n\nHere `review` means a GitButler review target, usually backed by a pull request\nor merge request. It does not mean \"perform a code review\".\n\nSupported targets:\n\n```sh\nbut agentlog sessions branch <branch-name-or-ref> --limit 5\nbut agentlog sessions review <review-id-or-pull-request-key> --limit 5\nbut agentlog sessions change <change-id-or-key> --limit 5\n```\n\nImportant fields:\n\n- `session_key`: handle for follow-up reads.\n- `latest_captured_at`: freshness signal.\n- `record_count` and `turn_count`: rough size estimate before hydration.\n- `related_turn_keys`: turns with direct target evidence.\n- `match_evidence`: why the session was returned.\n- `observed_targets`: branch, review/PR/MR, or change keys observed in related\n  turns.\n- `latest_user_preview` and `latest_assistant_preview`: quick intent/result\n  scan.\n\nRelated sessions are sorted by latest activity. Treat this as relevance by\nfreshness, not proof of ownership.\n\n### Reading `show`\n\nUse `show` to answer \"what happened in this session?\" or \"what exactly\nhappened inside this turn?\"\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:21:32.917Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}